This morning on @realmoney An Honest And Still Ursine Market View * At the market highs the S&P Index was approximately 15%-20% overvalued * The S&P Index (according to my calculus) remains about 10%-15% overvalued (current price: 3230, fair market value of about 2850)

* But, with the concentrated outperformance of the market generals v. the soldiers (and the historic spread between value and growth), a few individual stocks are already back into my buy zones (using an intermediate term investing horizon) * Yesterday, under the influence of an

unimaginable Black Swan and with so many on the same side of the bullish boat (thanks to ETFs and risk parity) - the ugly side of the market was exposed * The risks associated with an evolving change in market structure (and the introduction of no commission trading) continues

to led me to expect more "flash crashes" and a heightened regime of volatility * Consensus 2020 S&P EPS expectations are far too high - just like a year ago * Given the plethora of uncertainties, I find it difficult not to expect some mean reversion (lower) in valuations this

year * Above average cash returns is the street where I live today - it's a destination many should consider. @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @michaelsantoli @riskreversal @Sarge986 @carlquintanilla @davidfaber @lizclaman @bobpisani
